WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.560
Okay, so as you know we are going up the OSI model layers and we are at Layer 2, the

00:29.560 --> 00:37.880
data link. Okay, so as you know we are going up the OSI model layers and we

00:37.880 --> 00:43.600
are at Layer 2, the data link layer, and there are some significant protocols that

00:43.600 --> 00:48.680
operate at Layer 2 that we can think of from a security perspective. Now if you

00:48.680 --> 00:54.000
remember back in the old days when the only way to get into a network

00:54.000 --> 01:00.240
remotely was to use dial up lines and modems, the industry had a problem. The

01:00.240 --> 01:06.200
problem was how do we allow TCP IP to run across dial up lines? So the industry

01:06.200 --> 01:12.600
had to come up with a protocol that would allow TCP IP and its protocols to

01:12.600 --> 01:18.560
run across dial up line. As you know dial up lines are analog connections and

01:18.560 --> 01:23.040
so they had to create a protocol that would allow that and what they came up

01:23.040 --> 01:28.720
with is something called slip. Serial line interface protocol is what that

01:28.720 --> 01:34.920
stands for. Now eventually when remote access became really popular they

01:34.920 --> 01:40.480
decided to replace this protocol with something better because as companies

01:40.480 --> 01:46.080
started to offer remote access to everyone and it became a necessity for all

01:46.080 --> 01:53.040
organizations. They decided to replace that older slip protocol with something

01:53.040 --> 01:58.280
that is much better and what they called it is what you see here PPP point to

01:58.280 --> 02:04.240
point protocol. Now by the time they did this they realized that a lot of companies

02:04.240 --> 02:10.080
were offering remote access and what they should do with this protocol because it

02:10.080 --> 02:15.680
was going to be used for remote access is build some authentication protocols

02:15.680 --> 02:21.360
right into this PPP protocol because they realized that this would be used by

02:21.360 --> 02:28.760
people that would be connecting in remotely by using for example VPNs and so they

02:28.760 --> 02:35.080
decided to build three authentication protocols as part of the PPP

02:35.080 --> 02:40.520
authentication protocol itself or remote access protocol itself and they gave

02:40.520 --> 02:45.640
us three instead of one and the reason that there are three is because they all

02:45.640 --> 02:50.480
provide different levels of security as you'll see and this is something that's

02:50.480 --> 02:55.760
important for you to focus on. The first one the first authentication protocol

02:55.760 --> 03:02.920
that they built natively into PPP is called PAP password authentication protocol.

03:02.920 --> 03:09.280
This one is the simplest but it's also the least secure. In fact what this

03:09.280 --> 03:16.920
uses is a plain text reusable static password in order to authenticate the

03:16.920 --> 03:21.520
individual at the other end that's trying to connect remotely. Now if you think

03:21.520 --> 03:27.560
about those three words that I just use plain text reusable static those are not

03:27.560 --> 03:33.600
good security words but that's all that PAP supports and so what it does is it

03:33.600 --> 03:39.040
sends your password across the line in plain text so if there's anybody in

03:39.040 --> 03:44.120
between like there is likely to be they can see your password and here's the

03:44.120 --> 03:48.920
real problem we can never change that password you cannot force a password

03:48.920 --> 03:54.560
change so PAP is not very good and you wonder why did we even have it but it is

03:54.560 --> 04:00.400
supported by a lot of simple network devices and in fact in the early days of

04:00.400 --> 04:04.800
remote access this was really the only option for people and companies to

04:04.800 --> 04:11.000
offer remote access and it's still widely used by many applications. What's better

04:11.000 --> 04:17.040
is the second one it's called CHAP challenge handshake authentication protocol.

04:17.040 --> 04:23.080
What this one does is it addresses some of the problems that EAP does or has and

04:23.080 --> 04:28.840
so when we send the password across the line using CHAP it is encrypted and

04:28.840 --> 04:35.880
you can force people to change passwords every 30 days or every 60 days or

04:35.880 --> 04:40.680
whatever it is that the company decides on and so it's a much more secure

04:40.680 --> 04:46.080
protocol in fact it is very popular out there even today for organizations that

04:46.080 --> 04:51.760
offer remote access through VPNs because ultimately this person sitting

04:51.760 --> 04:56.880
behind that VPN needs to be authenticated and a lot of companies have

04:56.880 --> 05:02.360
standardized on the CHAP protocol as part of for example their radius and

05:02.360 --> 05:08.040
tax and diameter administration systems that companies will implement in

05:08.040 --> 05:13.080
order to host remote access but CHAP much better and in fact it also supports

05:13.080 --> 05:18.760
two factor authentication which has become pre-standard for organizations to

05:18.760 --> 05:24.520
use in order to allow remote access. The best one is actually the third one and

05:24.520 --> 05:31.600
it's called EAP and the reason it's the best is because of the E the E stands for

05:31.600 --> 05:39.760
extensible and so it can be adaptable it can be changed so almost address

05:39.760 --> 05:44.880
anything that an organization might want from a remote access perspective so

05:44.880 --> 05:50.040
that the way that they built EAP is that it's very flexible you can use it in

05:50.040 --> 05:56.160
conjunction with almost anything else and so you see it a lot today in any

05:56.160 --> 06:02.280
service that requires remote access in fact the next slide here gives us an

06:02.280 --> 06:09.480
idea of EAP and how good it is there is one version of it that you would be wise

06:09.480 --> 06:17.680
to understand as we have seen it appear on the exam and that is P EAP and the

06:17.680 --> 06:24.600
P is actually for protected EAP and so what they do with this one is they

06:24.600 --> 06:32.480
protect the EAP traffic across a SSL and TLS tunnel in other words the EAP

06:32.480 --> 06:37.240
traffic that contains your authentication information is actually protected by

06:37.240 --> 06:42.720
using the SSL slash TLS protocol which provides authentication and

06:42.720 --> 06:47.800
encryption and possibly some other things so remember P EAP which stands for

06:47.800 --> 06:55.920
protected EAP simply tunnels the EAP traffic across a SSL slash TLS tunnel but

06:55.920 --> 07:03.200
here's why EAP is so extensible there are many versions of it that the

07:03.200 --> 07:07.960
industry has come up with to really suit any remote access capability that any

07:07.960 --> 07:16.640
organization or service might require so we've got EAP TLS we've got EAP T TLS

07:16.640 --> 07:23.240
and we've got EAP P EAP which we just talked about we've got lightweight EAP as

07:23.240 --> 07:29.680
well and they all provide as you can see here different levels of allowing

07:29.680 --> 07:35.840
remote entities to authenticate through the EAP protocol but do it in such a

07:35.840 --> 07:41.640
way so that it becomes very efficient for the organization that's hosting the

07:41.640 --> 07:47.380
remote access requirements there's even a EAP MD5 which really addresses the

07:47.380 --> 07:53.320
integrity of that traffic as it goes through for example the EAP authentication

07:53.320 --> 07:59.080
information even though we've provided a really good slide here probably the

07:59.080 --> 08:04.640
one that is the most important for you to remember is P EAP that we've talked

08:04.640 --> 08:11.080
about just before now we're still at layer 2 and what we need to understand at

08:11.080 --> 08:17.440
layer 2 are some of the significant devices and protocols that operate at

08:17.440 --> 08:22.800
layer 2 of the OSI model and as far as devices are concerned really two of

08:22.920 --> 08:28.840
them that are significant bridges and switches both operate at layer 2 and

08:28.840 --> 08:34.440
therefore because they operate at layer 2 they are still very efficient but

08:34.440 --> 08:39.160
they are really dumb devices in other words we can't really ask any of these

08:39.160 --> 08:43.880
devices to make any security decisions they just don't have the intelligence to

08:43.880 --> 08:49.040
be able to do that but both bridges and switches are layer 2 devices now don't

08:49.040 --> 08:54.360
overthink these questions because as you know today companies can buy layer

08:54.360 --> 08:59.880
3 switches they can buy layer 4 switches you can even buy layer 7 switches but

08:59.880 --> 09:05.800
unless the exam specifically mentions those words you need to remember that a

09:05.800 --> 09:11.920
switch natively operates at layer 2 and they are both bridges and switches

09:11.920 --> 09:17.160
dumb devices in fact that's why we call them bridges they simply bridge two

09:17.160 --> 09:22.280
things together and that bridge does not care what's going across it it has

09:22.280 --> 09:27.960
no ability to interpret it so these are very fast devices but we cannot use

09:27.960 --> 09:32.800
them to make any sort of security decisions switches have a little more

09:32.800 --> 09:37.440
functionality than bridges do because of the ports that are available at the

09:37.440 --> 09:42.560
back of a switch and so if you connect devices to the ports that are at the

09:42.560 --> 09:46.880
back of the switch it starts giving us the ability to start creating what

09:46.880 --> 09:52.160
are called segments or virtual lands as we will discuss later when we get into

09:52.160 --> 09:59.800
the partitioning and segmentation aspect of network security now these are

09:59.800 --> 10:06.640
some of the other layer 2 protocols that are noteworthy at layer 2 and you'll

10:06.640 --> 10:12.320
know that some of these are layer 2 for sure because they are called L2 L2

10:12.320 --> 10:19.800
TP obviously the L2 stands for layer 2 but PPTP also a layer 2 tunneling

10:19.800 --> 10:26.280
protocol we just described what slip was that older protocol that was used for

10:26.280 --> 10:31.640
remote access that was eventually replaced by the PPP protocol that contains

10:31.640 --> 10:38.440
those authentication protocols that we just talked about PAP, CHAP and EAP also

10:38.440 --> 10:45.080
at this layer is what we call ARP and reverse ARP and those are some significant

10:45.080 --> 10:52.040
protocols that operate at layer 2 what ARP does is it maps IP addresses which

10:52.040 --> 10:58.240
is the logical addressing that's used across networking to specific MAC

10:58.240 --> 11:04.360
addresses which is what makes you unique on any network and so as something

11:04.360 --> 11:09.960
comes in as an IP address the network has to take that and map it to the

11:09.960 --> 11:15.880
correct MAC address and that's what ARP does now when we originate a outgoing

11:15.880 --> 11:20.680
request from the internal network it obviously originates from your MAC

11:20.680 --> 11:25.760
address but that has to be converted to the correct IP address which is what

11:25.760 --> 11:31.720
reverse ARP does but both ARP and reverse ARP are layer 2 protocols that work

11:31.720 --> 11:41.920
basically together now L2F PPTP L2TP or what we call tunneling protocols tunneling

11:41.920 --> 11:47.440
protocols simply take something and encapsulate them within something else and

11:47.440 --> 11:53.640
we'll learn later that this is the precursor for how we create and use VPNs

11:53.640 --> 11:59.400
because VPNs require tunneling first and then encryption so these protocols

11:59.400 --> 12:06.320
that you see here L2F PPTP L2TP are layer 2 tunneling protocols and

12:06.320 --> 12:11.520
because they operate at layer 2 they are still very efficient but they may

12:11.520 --> 12:17.160
lack in functionality as you know the lower down the layers we go the less we

12:17.160 --> 12:22.280
can do but the more efficient we become the higher up you go the more we can

12:22.280 --> 12:27.160
do the more functional we become but the less efficient we become so these are

12:27.160 --> 12:32.120
very efficient tunneling protocols that operate at layer 2 but may be limited

12:32.120 --> 12:36.360
in some of the functionality that they can offer

